  <li id="comment-18125" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/04441403338356430549" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">ak</a></cite></div>
      <a href="index.html?p=869#comment-18125"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2011-12-30T02:42:46-05:00">Friday, December 30, 2011 at 2:42 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I ate this cake, too!  Seriously, what an amazing cake.  I found this cake because I wanted a nice marmalade cake for tea with a friend, and yours was the most appealing of all that I saw, partly because of the olive oil, and the bitterness.  So, I made the cake, but my friend ended up canceling the trip, which left me with one huge cake.  First I nibbled at it for tea, then ate some after dinner, then a bit with my morning tea, and by the time the afternoon had rolled around, a quarter cake had been gone.  So I promptly froze half, and gave the other quarter away.  Since then, however, I have been obsessed, and have started on a few variations.  First off, I added a marmalade glaze (blood orange), which was marvelous and because the edges were slightly crisp when I took it out of the oven (the centre took a while to set), it softened them to yield a nice chewy finish, which was the best bit of the cake.  </p>
<p>I also took full advantage of the current citrus crop, and used meyer lemons and some cara cara (red navel) oranges, and then did my own kumquat glaze along with candied kumquats.  plus, i switched out the pistachios.  This version is what I served after our Christmas dinner (a different take on a fruit and nut cake), and my family went crazy for it!  And you are right &#8211; even better the day after.  Thanks so much for this recipe, it has now become my go-to cake within  a span of 3 weeks.</p>
    </div>

